A
Appointment Supply (appt/wk)
= IF THEN ELSE(User defined Appointment Supply<0,"Appointment Supply (75th percentile)",IF THEN ELSE(Time<Experiment wk, "Appointment Supply (75th percentile)", User defined Appointment Supply))
Description: Total number of 60 minute Psychotherapy appointments offered by the team each wk.
Present in 1 view:
  • Supply Used
Used by:
  • Appointments Available for New Patients - All remaining supply, after all existing patients are seen. Users can also set aside additional appointments specifically for new patients, which allows the team to start more patients (i.e., they receive a first visit) than they can initiate (i.e., they receive a second visit). It is prevented from going below zero.
  • Appointments for Existing Patients - The number of appointments used by existing patients each week. The team either satisfies all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or uses all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply), leaving no appointments available for new patients. (appt/wk)
  • Completing Rate - Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)
  • Supply Available for New Pts who can start 2nd visit - All remaining supply, after all existing patients are seen and taking new patient carve-outs into account. It is prevented from going below zero.

Appointments Available for New Patients (appt/wk)
= MAX((Appointment Supply-Appointments for Existing Patients),0)+STEP(Reserve Appointments for New Patients,Experiment wk)
Description: All remaining supply, after all existing patients are seen. Users can also set aside additional appointments specifically for new patients, which allows the team to start more patients (i.e., they receive a first visit) than they can initiate (i.e., they receive a second visit). It is prevented from going below zero.
Present in 2 views:
  • Supply Used
  • Psychotherapy Service
Used by:

  • Percieved New pts appt Supply - Schedulers' perceptsion of the appointment supply available for new patients, regardless of the capacity for them to continue care.
  • Starting Psychotherapy - The number of patients who start Psychotherapy each wk, based on the actual appointment supply available to new patients (including any user adjustments to both "Appointment Supply" and "Additional Supply for New Patients).

C (pts)
= ("Starters Who Return Later %")* SankeyScalar
Description: For the Sankey - reporting out the base case value for the total number of patients in the cohort who meet the criteria defining this state.
Present in 1 view:
  • UI Outputs
Used by:
  • This is a supplementary variable.
Used by:
  • "Appointment Supply (75th percentile)" - The number of appointments available with this team for each service each week. The estimate is calculated using the volume of visits completed each week with the team in each service over one year. (appt/wk)
  • "AUD within 3 months %" - An estimate of the proportion of the team's patients with alchohol use disorder (AUD), calculated from the cohort of patients who completed visits charted with a primary diagnosis of AUD within their entire psychotherapy engagement. (pct)
  • "Completers Who Graduate %" - Of patients who complete eight or more psychotherapy visits within their first three months (i.e., completers), this is the proportion who do not return for any more psychotherapy visits after three months (i.e., patients who graduate). (pct)
  • "DEP within 3 months %" - An estimate of the proportion of the team's patients with depression (DEP), calculated from the cohort of patients who completed visits charted with a primary diagnosis of DEP within their entire psychotherapy engagement. (pct)
  • "ET - From 1 Visit (1st Quartile)" - The median of the lower quartile of engagement durations of patients who (after completing only 1 visit in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • "ET - From 1 Visit (4th Quartile)" - The median of the upper quartile of engagement durations of patients who (after completing only 1 visit in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • "ET - From 1 Visit (Mean)" - The median of the inner two quartiles of engagement durations of patients who (after completing only 1 visit in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • "ET - From 2 to 7 Visits (1st Quartile)" - The median of the lower quartile of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 2-7 visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • "ET - From 2 to 7 Visits (4th Quartile)" - The median of the upper quartile of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 2-7 visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • "ET - From 2 to 7 Visits (Mean)" - The median of the inner two quartiles of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 2-7 visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • "ET - From 8 or More Visits (1st Quartile)" - The median of the lower quartile of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 8 or more visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • "ET - From 8 or More Visits (4th Quartile)" - The median of the upper quartile of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 2-7 visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • "ET - From 8 or More Visits (Mean)" - The median of the inner two quartiles of engagement durations of patients who (after completing 8 or more visits in their first 3 months) complete more visits in the subsequent months.
  • "ET - Initiators Who Complete" - Median engagement time estimated from the team's own data for patients in their 2-7th visit, who will go on to 8 or more visits in the first three months.
  • "ET - Initiators Who Quit Early" - Median engagement time estimated from the team's own data for patients in their 2-7th visit, who will not continue care after the first three months.
  • "Initiators Who Complete %" - Of patients who complete at least two to seven psychotherapy visits within three months (i.e., initiators), this is the proportion of patients who complete eight or more psychotherapy visits within three months (i.e., patients who complete a timely dose). (pct)
  • "Initiators Who Quit Early %" - Of patients who complete at least two to seven psychotherapy visits within their first three months (i.e., initiators), this is the proportion of patients who never complete another psychotherapy visit with this team (i.e., patients who quit before completing a timely dose). F,A

Completing Rate (appt/wk)
= Appointment Supply
Description: Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)
Present in 1 view:
  • Supply Used
Used by:
  • Appointments in Psychotherapy - The total number of appointments for psychotherapy on the calendar. (appts)
  • Ballpark Initial Appointments in Psychotherapy - The number of appointments on the calendar is not a meaningful measure of the system, so accuracy here is not necessary.

G
"User-defined Implement IOP" (Dmnl [0,1,1])
= GAME (0)
Description: Initiate an "Intensive Outpatient Program" for new patients, where they are seen twice as often for half as many weeks after they initiate care. Estimates from the team's data for Return Visit Interval and Median Engagement Duration during a patients first 3 months in care are modified accordingly. Also, this more intensive therapy results in more patients completing a timely dose, modifying patient flow percentages estimated from the team's data (specifically: the gap between the desired and current state for "Starters who Initiate %," "Initiators who Complete %," and "Completers who Graduate %" all increase by 30%, while the gap between the desired and current state for "Initiators who Quit Early %" is reduced by 30%). These changes do not affect patient care patterns for patients who remain in care after completing their timely dose of psychotherapy. A team can choose to "Partially" or "Fully" implement the IOP, where "Partial" indicates that only half their patients follow the IOP, and "Fully" indicates that all new patients follow the IOP. (pct)
Present in 2 views:
  • Supply Used
  • Psychotherapy Service
Used by:
  • "Effect of Implement IOP on Completer %" - The relative change for new patients following care pathways after initiating an Intensive Outpatient Program, starting in Week zero, delayed by the average time it takes to get to completion (now, with IOP is 6 weeks, instead of the usual 12 weeks).
  • Effect of Implement IOP on Durations - The relative change in patients' engagement durations after they initiate care caused by implementing an Intensive Outpatient Program.
  • Effect of Implement IOP on Frequency - The relative change in patients' visit frequency after they initiate care caused by implementing an Intensive Outpatient Program. Implementing IOP will not affect Sankey Bar heights, as doubling the frequency and halving the duration will cancel out when estimating patients' average total visits.
  • "Effect of Implement IOP on Initiator %s" - The relative change for new patients following care pathways after initiating an Intensive Outpatient Program, starting in Week zero.

"User-defined Initiators Who Quit Early %" (Dmnl [-0.05,1,0.05])
= GAME (-0.05)
Description: This slider controls the proportion of patients who, after initiating psychotherapy, then fail to complete a full dose (i.e., who never complete more than 7 visits total). This replaces the base case value estimated from the team's data. This value, plus the value of "Initiators who Complete %" should not sum to more than 100%, otherwise patients will be pursuing multiple engagement pathways simultaneously. Note, if these two percentages sum to 100%, that implies that no (zero percent) Initiators are returning later (i.e., completing there next appointment more than 3 months after they initiate). (pct)
Present in 1 view:
  • Psychotherapy Service
Used by:
  • "Actual Initiators Who Quit Early %" - Constrained to be between 0 and 100%.
Default psy i v21 2019 11 04
(Default)		 #305
G
"User-defined Starters Who Initiate %" (Dmnl [-0.05,1,0.05])
= GAME (-0.05)
Description: This slider controls the proportion of patients who, after starting psychotherapy, then go on to initiate (i.e., who complete at least 2 visits during their first three months). This replaces the base case value estimated from the team's data. This value, plus the value of "Starters Who Return Later %" should not sum to more than 100%, otherwise patients will be pursuing multiple engagement pathways simultaneously. Note, if these two percentages sum to 100%, that implies that no (zero percent) Starters are quitting early (i.e., the team has no "One-and-Dones"). (pct)

G
"User-defined Starters Who Return Later %" (Dmnl [-0.05,1,0.05])
= GAME (-0.05)
Description: This slider controls the proportion of patients who, after starting psychotherapy, then fail to initiate in a timely manner (i.e., who never complete another visit in their first three months, but do complete more visits later). This replaces the base case value estimated from the team's data. This value, plus the value of "Starters who Initiate %" should not sum to more than 100%, otherwise patients will be pursuing multiple engagement pathways simultaneously. Note, if these two percentages sum to 100%, that implies that no (zero percent) Starters are quitting early (i.e., the team has no "One-and-Dones"). (pct)
Present in 1 view:
  • Psychotherapy Service
Used by:
  • "Actual Starters Who Return Later %" - The percent of patients who return for more appointments in the subsequent three months after completing only one visit in their first three months. The percent of these "One-n-More Laters" is constrained between 0 and 100%.

    Ending who can Initiate = "<3mo Visit 1 who can start 2"/Median Time in Visit 1
    Starting Rate who can Initiate = Starting Psychotherapy who can start 2

Appointments in Psychotherapy = ∫Booking Rate-Completing Rate dt + [Ballpark Initial Appointments in Psychotherapy]
Ballpark Initial Appointments in Psychotherapy = Completing Rate * "Avg RVI >3mo"
    Booking Rate = Appointments Available for New Patients+Appointments for Existing Patients
    Completing Rate = Appointment Supply

"From Completers-HighD" = ∫From Completers into High D-From Completers Ending High D dt + [0]
    From Completers Ending High D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Completers-HighD", "Engagement Time - From 8 or More Visits (4th Quartile)"),0)
    From Completers into High D = "Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) from Patients in Over 7 Visits"*"Starting HighD %"

"From Completers-LowD" = ∫From Completers into Low D-From Completers Ending Low D dt + [0]
    From Completers Ending Low D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Completers-LowD", "Engagement Time - From 8 or More Visits (1st Quartile)"),0)
    From Completers into Low D = "Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) from Patients in Over 7 Visits"*"Starting LowD %"

"From Completers-MidD" = ∫From Completers into Mid D-From Completers Ending Mid D dt + [0]
    From Completers Ending Mid D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Completers-MidD", "Engagement Time - From 8 or More Visits (Mean)"),0)
    From Completers into Mid D = "Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) from Patients in Over 7 Visits"*"Starting MidD %"

"From Initiators-HighD" = ∫From Initiators into High D-From Initiators Ending High D dt + [0]
    From Initiators Ending High D = MAX(ZIDZ( "From Initiators-HighD", "Engagement Time - From 2 to 7 Visits (4th Quartile)"),0)
    From Initiators into High D = "Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) from Patients in Visit 2 to 7"*"Starting HighD %"

"From Initiators-LowD" = ∫From Initiators into Low D-From Initiators Ending Low D dt + [0]
    From Initiators Ending Low D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Initiators-LowD", "Engagement Time - From 2 to 7 Visits (1st Quartile)"),0)
    From Initiators into Low D = "Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) from Patients in Visit 2 to 7"*"Starting LowD %"

"From Initiators-MidD" = ∫From Initiators into Mid D-From Initiators Ending Mid D dt + [0]
    From Initiators Ending Mid D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Initiators-MidD", "Engagement Time - From 2 to 7 Visits (Mean)"),0)
    From Initiators into Mid D = "Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) from Patients in Visit 2 to 7"*"Starting MidD %"

"From Starters-HighD" = ∫From Starters into High D-From Starters Ending High D dt + [0]
    From Starters Ending High D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Starters-HighD", "Engagement Time - From 1 Visit (4th Quartile)"),0)
    From Starters into High D = "Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) From Patients in First Visit"*"Starting HighD %"

"From Starters-LowD" = ∫From Starters into Low D-From Starters Ending Low D dt + [0]
    From Starters Ending Low D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Starters-LowD", "Engagement Time - From 1 Visit (1st Quartile)"),0)
    From Starters into Low D = "Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) From Patients in First Visit"*"Starting LowD %"

"From Starters-MidD" = ∫From Starters into Mid D-From Starters Ending Mid D dt + [0]
    From Starters Ending Mid D = MAX(ZIDZ("From Starters-MidD", "Engagement Time - From 1 Visit (Mean)"),0)
    From Starters into Mid D = "Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) From Patients in First Visit"*"Starting MidD %"

Initiators who will Continue = ∫Initiation Rate who will Complete-Continuting on to Visit 8 Rate dt + [0]
    Continuting on to Visit 8 Rate = MAX(ZIDZ(Initiators who will Continue, ("ET - Initiators Who Complete"*Effect of Implement IOP on Durations)),0)
    Initiation Rate who will Complete = Ending who can Initiate*"Actual Starters who Initiate % including any IOP Effect"*"Actual Initiators who Complete % including IOP Effect"

Initiators who will Quit = ∫Initiation Rate who will Quit-Ending During Visit 2 to 7 Rate dt + [0]
    Ending During Visit 2 to 7 Rate = MAX(ZIDZ(Initiators who will Quit, ("ET - Initiators Who Quit Early"*Effect of Implement IOP on Durations)),0)
    Initiation Rate who will Quit = Ending who can Initiate*"Actual Starters who Initiate % including any IOP Effect"*"Actual Initiators Who Quit Early % including any IOP Effect"

Initiators who will Return = ∫Initation Rate who will Return-"Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) from Patients in Visit 2 to 7" dt + [0]
    "Continuing Treatment Rate (after 3 Months) from Patients in Visit 2 to 7" = MAX(Initiators who will Return/("ET - Initiators Who Return"*Effect of Implement IOP on Durations),0)
    Initation Rate who will Return = Ending who can Initiate*"Actual Starters who Initiate % including any IOP Effect"*(1-"Actual Initiators who Complete % including IOP Effect"-"Actual Initiators Who Quit Early % including any IOP Effect")

Patients in First Visit = ∫Starting Rate-Ending First Visit dt + [0]
    Ending First Visit = Patients in First Visit/Median Time in Visit 1
    Starting Rate = Starting Psychotherapy

Patients in Over 7 Visits = ∫Completion Rate-Ending After 8 or More Visits Rate dt + [0]
    Completion Rate = Continuting on to Visit 8 Rate
    Ending After 8 or More Visits Rate = MAX(ZIDZ(Patients in Over 7 Visits, ("ET - Completers who Graduate"*Effect of Implement IOP on Durations)),0)

†  Level Structure Report still under development.
